This probably wouldn't be a bad way to test if both characters had run speed 3 and jboots, so you could test both ways to detect if system/connection differences are skewing results or not. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/ubearberry.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Bearberry</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(12/11/01 4:18:46 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Fast Walk vs Jboots</span><hr size=1> I believe Frostmier is correct.  Your horizontal velocity remains the same regardless of the slope you are running on.  This makes sense from a programming standpoint since the server doesn't want to do this calculation:<br>
<br>
sqrt((x1-x2)^2+(y1-y2)^2+(z1-z2)^2)<br>
<br>
everytime someone moves.<br>
<br>
